Document: Animation Introduction
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This document provides a basic introduction to the animation system in Godot Engine.

This document provides a basic introduction to the animation system in Godot Engine. It covers the fundamental concepts and tools used for creating and managing animations within the engine. The animation system allows for the creation of complex visual sequences, character movements, UI animations, and more. Key components include the AnimationPlayer node, Animation resource, and the Animation panel. The AnimationPlayer node is responsible for playing back animations, while the Animation resource itself contains the actual animation data, such as keyframes for properties. The Animation panel in the editor provides a timeline-based interface for creating, editing, and previewing animations. Understanding these core elements is crucial for effectively utilizing Godot's animation capabilities.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to the animation features
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section introduces the AnimationPlayer node and outlines what users will learn in the animation tutorial series.
In this guide you learn to:
* Work with the Animation Panel
* Animate any property of any node
* Create a simple animation
In Godot, you can animate anything available in the Inspector, such as Node transforms, sprites, UI elements, particles, visibility and color of materials, and so on. You can also modify values of script variables and even call functions.
---CHUNK---
Document: AnimationPlayer node
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to create an AnimationPlayer node and introduces the basic components of the animation panel.
Inherits: Node
The AnimationPlayer node type is the data container for your animations. One AnimationPlayer node can hold multiple animations, which can automatically transition to one another.

After you create an AnimationPlayer node, click on it to open the Animation Panel at the bottom of the viewport.

The animation panel consists of four parts:
- Animation controls (i.e. add, load, save, and delete animations)
- The tracks listing
- The timeline with keyframes
- The timeline and track controls, where you can zoom the timeline and edit tracks, for example.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains the fundamental concepts of keyframes, timelines, and animation tracks in Godot Engine.
Computer animation relies on keyframes. A keyframe defines the value of a property at a point in time. Diamond shapes represent keyframes in the timeline. A line between two keyframes indicates that the value doesn't change between them. You set values of a node's properties and create animation keyframes for them. When the animation runs, the engine will interpolate the values between the keyframes, resulting in them gradually changing over time. The timeline defines how long the animation will take. You can insert keyframes at various points, and change their timing. Each line in the Animation Panel is an animation track that references a Normal or Transform property of a node. Each track stores a path to a node and its affected property. For example, the position track in the illustration refers to the position property of the Sprite2D node. Tip: If you animate the wrong property, you can edit a track's path at any time by double-clicking on it and typing the new path. Play the animation using the "Play from beginning" button (or pressing Shift + D on keyboard) to see the changes instantly.
---CHUNK---
Document: Creating a simple animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This tutorial introduces the basics of creating simple animations in Godot Engine.

This tutorial will guide you through the process of creating a simple animation in Godot. We will cover the essential steps to bring objects to life within your game.

First, ensure you have a scene set up with the node you wish to animate. For this example, let's assume you have a Sprite2D node.

1.  **Select the Node**: In the Scene dock, select the Sprite2D node.
2.  **Add an AnimationPlayer**: In the Node dock, click the "Add Child Node" button and search for "AnimationPlayer". Add it as a child of your Sprite2D. The AnimationPlayer node is responsible for managing all animations for its parent and its children.
3.  **Open the Animation Panel**: At the bottom of the Godot editor, you will see several tabs. Click on the "Animation" tab to open the animation panel. If you don't see it, you might need to select the AnimationPlayer node first.
4.  **Create a New Animation**: In the animation panel, click the "Animation" button (it might say "Make New" if no animation exists) and select "New". A dialog will pop up asking you to name your animation. Let's name it "move".
5.  **Set Animation Length**: You can set the length of your animation using the "Length" property in the animation panel. For this example, let's set it to 1.0 seconds.
6.  **Set Keyframes**:
    *   **Position Keyframe**: With the "move" animation selected, click the "Key" button next to the "Position" property of your Sprite2D node in the Inspector. Choose "Create Key" for the Position property. This will add a keyframe at the current time (0.0s) at the current position. Now, move the playhead in the animation panel to the end of the animation (1.0s). Select your Sprite2D node and move it to a new position in the 2D editor. With the Sprite2D selected, click the "Key" button next to "Position" again and select "Create Key". This records the new position at the end of the animation.
    *   **Rotation Keyframe**: Repeat the process for the "Rotation Degrees" property. At 0.0s, add a keyframe. Move the playhead to 1.0s, rotate the Sprite2D, and add another keyframe for Rotation Degrees.
    *   **Scale Keyframe**: Similarly, add keyframes for the "Scale" property. At 0.0s, add a keyframe. Move to 1.0s, scale the Sprite2D, and add another keyframe.
7.  **Play the Animation**: You can now press the "Play" button in the animation panel to see your animation in action. The Sprite2D should move, rotate, and scale over the course of 1 second.

This basic workflow allows you to animate any property of any node in Godot. You can add more keyframes, change interpolation modes, and create complex sequences.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section describes the initial scene setup for an animation tutorial, including adding a Sprite2D and an AnimationPlayer, and explains a key rule regarding AnimationPlayer's inheritance.
Scene setup
For this tutorial, we'll create a Sprite node with an AnimationPlayer as its child. We will animate the sprite to move between two points on the screen.
Note: AnimationPlayer inherits from Node instead of Node2D or Node3D, which means that the child nodes will not inherit the transform from the parent nodes due to a bare Node being present in the hierarchy.
Key Rule: It is not recommended to add nodes that have a 2D/3D transform as a child of an AnimationPlayer node.
The sprite holds an image texture. For this tutorial, select the Sprite2D node, click Texture in the Inspector, and then click Load. Select the default Godot icon for the sprite's texture.
---CHUNK---
Document: Animation tutorials
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to add a new animation to an AnimationPlayer node.

To add a new animation, select the AnimationPlayer node. Click the "Animation" button in the animation editor. From the list, select "New" to add a new animation. Enter a name for the animation in the dialog box.
---CHUNK---
Document: Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how animations are managed and registered within animation libraries in Godot.

Animations are registered in a list within the animation library resource for reusability. When an animation is added to an AnimationPlayer without specific settings, it is registered in the default [Global] animation library. If multiple animation libraries exist and an animation is added, a dialog box will prompt the user to choose options for adding the new animation.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to add a new animation track for a node's position in the Godot animation editor.

To add a new track for a sprite, select the sprite node and examine the toolbar. Buttons and switches in the toolbar allow you to add keyframes for the selected node's location, rotation, and scale. For animating only the sprite's position, ensure only the location switch is selected. Selected switches appear blue.

Click the key button to create the first keyframe. If a track for the Position property does not yet exist, Godot will prompt you to create it. Click **Create**. Godot will then create a new track and place the first keyframe at the beginning of the timeline.
---CHUNK---
Document: Animation Introduction
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to set the animation length and create a second keyframe for sprite movement.

To set the animation length, change the animation length to 2 in the controls on the right side of the animation panel's timeline header.

Move the sprite to its final position using the Move tool or by setting the Position's X value in the Inspector.

Click on the timeline header near the two-second mark in the animation panel and then click the key button in the toolbar to create the second keyframe.
---CHUNK---
