Document: AnimationPlayer
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to set an animation to autoplay when a scene loads.
To make an animation play automatically when the AnimationPlayer node's scene starts or joins another scene, click the "Autoplay on load" button in the animation editor. This button is located next to the edit button. The icon for the autoplay animation will also appear in front of its name in the animation list, allowing for easy identification.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: Explains how Godot's animation looping works when the end keyframe is not explicitly set, causing the animation to play forwards and backwards.
When Animation Looping is enabled and no keyframe is specified at the end of an animation, the first keyframe also serves as the last. This allows the animation to play from the last keyframe back to the first, creating a back-and-forth motion. For example, an animation extended to four seconds with this setting will have Godot calculate frames moving the sprite back and forth. The behavior of animation looping can be modified by changing the track's loop mode, which is detailed in the subsequent chapter.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Animation Tracks
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: Explains the settings for animation tracks, including update modes, interpolation types, and loop modes.

Track settings have a panel at the end to configure update mode, track interpolation, and loop mode.

The update mode determines when property values are updated.
- Continuous: Updates the property on each frame.
- Discrete: Updates the property only at keyframes.
- Capture: If the first keyframe's time is greater than 0.0, the current property value is remembered and blended with the first animation key. This can be used to move a node from its current position to a specific location.

"Continuous" mode is typically used. "Discrete" and "Capture" are for complex animations.

Track interpolation defines how values between keyframes are calculated. Supported modes are:
- Nearest: Uses the value of the nearest keyframe.
- Linear: Calculates the value based on a linear function between keyframes.
- Cubic: Calculates the value based on a cubic function between keyframes.
- Linear Angle: Linear mode specifically for rotation, using the shortest path.
- Cubic Angle: Cubic mode specifically for rotation, using the shortest path.

Cubic interpolation results in slower animation at keyframes and faster movement between them, creating more natural motion, commonly used for character animation. Linear interpolation provides a fixed pace, resulting in a more robotic effect.

Godot supports two loop modes for animations set to loop:
- Clamp loop interpolation: The animation stops at the last keyframe for the track. When the first keyframe is reached again, the animation resets to its initial values.
- Wrap loop interpolation: Godot calculates the animation after the last keyframe to smoothly transition back to the values of the first keyframe.
---CHUNK---
Document: introduction
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to animate any property of a node in Godot by using keyframes in the Inspector.

You can animate any property of a node in Godot, not just position, rotation, and scale. When the animation panel is visible and a node is selected, a keyframe button appears in the Inspector next to each animatable property. Clicking this button adds a track and a keyframe to the current animation for that specific property.
---CHUNK---
Document: Animation Tutorials
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to edit keyframes in the animation timeline, including their values and easing curves.
Edit keyframes
You can click on a keyframe in the animation timeline to display and edit its value in the Inspector.
You can also edit the easing value for a keyframe here by clicking and dragging its easing curve. This tells Godot how to interpolate the animated property when it reaches this keyframe.
You can tweak your animations this way until the movement "looks right."
---CHUNK---
Document: Animation Tutorials
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use RESET animations in Godot to define default poses for properties and how this affects saving and resetting tracks in the editor.
Using RESET tracks
You can set up a special RESET animation to contain the "default pose". This is used to ensure that the default pose is restored when you save the scene and open it again in the editor.

For existing tracks, you can add an animation called "RESET" (case-sensitive), then add tracks for each property that you want to reset. The only keyframe should be at time 0, and give it the desired default value for each track.

If AnimationPlayer's Reset On Save property is set to true, the scene will be saved with the effects of the reset animation applied (as if it had been seeked to time 0.0). This only affects the saved file – the property tracks in the editor stay where they were.

If you want to reset the tracks in the editor, select the AnimationPlayer node, open the Animation bottom panel then choose Apply Reset in the animation editor's Edit dropdown menu.

When using the keyframe icon next to a property in the inspector the editor will ask you to automatically create a RESET track.
Note: RESET tracks are also used as reference values for blending. See also For better blending.
---CHUNK---
Document: Introduction to Animation
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use the onion skinning feature in Godot's animation editor.
The animation editor allows you to use onion skinning while creating an animation. To turn this feature on, click on the onion icon in the top right of the animation editor. Transparent red copies of the animated object's previous positions will then appear.

The three dots button next to the onion skinning button opens a dropdown menu that lets you adjust how it works, including the ability to use onion skinning for future frames.
---CHUNK---
Document: Animation Markers
Path: godot/tutorials/animation/introduction.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use animation markers in Godot to play specific parts of an animation and how to preview these sections.
Animation markers can be used to play a specific part of an animation rather than the whole thing. For example, if an animation file contains a character performing two distinct actions, and the project requires playing the whole animation as well as each action individually, markers can be placed on the timeline. This avoids the need to create additional animations for each action.

To add a marker to an animation, right-click the space above the timeline and select **Insert Marker...**.

All markers require a unique name within the animation. You can also set the color of the markers for improved organization.

To play the part of the animation between two markers, use the play_section_with_markers() and play_section_with_markers_backwards() methods. If no start marker is specified, the beginning of the animation is used. If no end marker is specified, the end of the animation is used.

If the end marker is placed after the end of the animation, the AnimationPlayer will clamp the end of the section so it does not go past the end of the animation.

To preview the animation between two markers, use Shift + Click to select the markers. When two markers are selected, the space between them will be highlighted in red.

When markers are selected for preview, the animation playback buttons will behave as if the selected area is the entire animation. Play Animation from Start will treat the first selected marker as the start of the animation, Play Animation Backwards from End will treat the second selected marker as the end, and so on.